TITLE: Measuring Function Performance with web-sys in Rust WebAssembly
DESCRIPTION: Example of importing and using the Performance API from the web-sys crate to measure execution time of a Rust function when compiled to WebAssembly. The code demonstrates how to access window.performance, get timestamps using now(), and calculate elapsed time.
SOURCE: https://github.com/rustwasm/wasm-bindgen/blob/main/guide/src/examples/performance.md#2025-04-16_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: rust
CODE:
```
use wasm_bindgen::prelude::*;
use web_sys::Performance;

#[wasm_bindgen(start)]
pub fn run() {
    // Here we want to utilize `window.performance.now()` to get the time before/after
    // we execute a long-running task to get an idea of how much time it took.
    //
    // First up we need to get a handle to `window.performance` which is what is going
    // to give us timing information.
    let performance = web_sys::window()
        .expect("should have a Window")
        .performance()
        .expect("should have a Performance");

    // Next up we measure how long it takes to sort a large-ish array. Note that this
    // timing isn't super precise, but should give a general idea of how long this
    // function takes in the grand scheme of things.
    let start = performance.now();
    let mut arr = Vec::new();
    for i in 0..1_000_000 {
        arr.push(i);
    }
    arr.sort();
    let elapsed = performance.now() - start;

    // And now that we've measured our timing let's add it to the document so we can
    // see what happened
    log!(
        "it took {} milliseconds to sort {} numbers",
        elapsed,
        arr.len()
    );
}
```

