TITLE: Implementing Synchronous WebAssembly Instantiation in JavaScript
DESCRIPTION: This JavaScript code, running in a Web Worker, demonstrates synchronous WebAssembly instantiation. It fetches the Wasm file, compiles and instantiates it synchronously, and then calls the 'add' function from the Rust code.
SOURCE: https://github.com/rustwasm/wasm-bindgen/blob/main/guide/src/examples/synchronous-instantiation.md#2025-04-16_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
importScripts("./pkg/synchronous_instantiation.js");

self.onmessage = async (e) => {
  // We need to make sure that `wasm_bindgen` is ready to be used.
  await wasm_bindgen();

  // Since `wasm_bindgen(...)` function does not actually instantiate
  // the Wasm module, but rather prepares it to be instantiated,
  // we can use `wasm_bindgen.wasm` to get the underlying `WebAssembly.Module`.
  console.log(wasm_bindgen.wasm);

  // `WebAssembly.Module` can be instantiated synchronously.
  const { instance } = new WebAssembly.Instance(wasm_bindgen.wasm, wasm_bindgen.imports);

  // Instance exports is what `wasm_bindgen(...)` usually returns,
  // so let's use it to initialize our exports.
  wasm_bindgen.init(instance.exports);

  // Now we can use our exports!
  const result = wasm_bindgen.add(1, 2);
  self.postMessage(result);
};
```

